<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-01-29T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-01-29T10:00:00-05:00" n="206" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d206">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">868.01/199: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase—Extract]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-01-29T17:00:00+02:00"><hi rend="italic">January 29,
                                        1924—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received January 29—4:07
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>29. … This morning I delivered letter to Minister for Foreign
                                Affairs.<note n="6" xml:id="d206fn6">See telegram no. 13, Jan. 26,
                                to the Chargé in Greece, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> He
                            expressed his gratification and stated that similar instructions would
                            be sent to the Greek Chargé in Washington.<note n="7" xml:id="d206fn7">The <hi rend="italic">note verbale</hi> from the Greek Chargé
                                presenting his letter of credence to the Secretary of State is dated
                                Feb. 4, 1924 (file no. 701.6811/158).</note> …</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>